Rating: 3
This was amazing! If you like Indian food and are a fan of chaat you will go ape over this one. I made it as outlined, and as we were eating, I realized that I had forgotten to add in the beans. Beanless, it was ok as a lighter side dish served with the baked wrapped tilapia on this site. Next time, and I definitely envision many next times, I will use chickpeas and serve on the side a dollop of plain yougurt dusted with paprika. Yumm.

Rating: 3
I really enjoyed this, but I'm a huge fan of dried beans. I reduced this for my family of 4 and reduced everything proportionately except the onions. To 2 cans of beans I added about 2 Tbsp. of finely chopped red onion. I didn't have cumin seeds and just used ground cumin. Over red leaf lettuce this was a simple, enjoyable salad with grilled garlic chicken and spicy mango salsa. I thought it was fine left over.

Rating: 3
This makes a very big batch, at least twice what my ten friends could eat, even though it is very good. The walnuts added a nice crunch, but they didn't work really well as leftovers because they got soggy. Next time, I'll make a bit less and also add some chopped celery for a bit of extra crunch. I am one of those unfortunate people to whom cilantro tastes like soap, so I substituted flat leaf parsley, which was perfect.

Rating: 3
I hate kidney beans so I substituted pinto beans because I knew they would be tasty with cilantro. We are also allergic to walnuts so I used pecans instead! It was fabulous and everyone in this household loved it!

Rating: 3
Very tasty. Nice to have the crunch of the walnuts in there, and the toasted cumin seeds give it a lovely, almost smokey flavor.